IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: To support the Oakland Museum of California
IRS990.MissionDesc: The Oakland Museum Women's Board is a California non-profit, public benefit corporation whose sole purpose is to provide services and funds to the Oakland Museum of California.
IRS990.Desc: The Oakland Museum Women's Board gives grants to the Oakland Museum of California to support education programs, fund exhibits, purchase items for the collection, conserve collection material, and support capital improvements and community outreach. The grants are funded by money raised at The Oakland Museum Women's Board's (OMWB) annual White Elephant Sale. Throughout the year, donated merchandise is sorted and arranged for sale in our 96,000 square foot warehouse. The dedicated work by nearly 1,000 volunteers is managed by the OMWB, which also handles the logistics of marketing, purchasing supplies, cashiering, coordinating with city services, arranging parking, handling insurance, human resources, security, building maintenance, community relations, etc.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The Organization has evaluated its current tax positions as of June 30, 2018 and is not aware of any significant uncertain tax positions for which a reserve would be necessary.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Grantmaker's Description of How Grants are Used
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: All original grant contracts are signed by the Project Director and the grantee. A letter from the President authorizes the Treasurer to transfer the funds to the grantee. At the end of the grant, the grantee provides a brief narrative report to the organization's Board, which is signed by the Project Director and is accompanied by a project financial report with attachments.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 4: Description of Significant Changes to Organizational Documents
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: In the fiscal year 2017 to 2018, the Bylaws were amended to remove the responsibility of the orientation of new members as well as maintaining membership participation records from the First Vice Presidents responsibilities, and added the Long Range Strategic Planning Chair to the Executive Committee.Additional changes included removing the specific number of additional members from the Membership Committee, putting the Chairs listed as Standing Committees in alphabetical order, eliminating the description of who can serve on the Audit Committee by referring instead to the OMWB Internal Control Policies, and clarified the role of the Information Systems Committee by stating that the resources it manages may include, but are not limited to, computer hardware, software, data and networks.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 6: Explanation of Classes of Members or Shareholder
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Per the organization's bylaws, voting members have equal power and voting rights. Associate and emeritus members do not have voting rights. Voting members may elect the members of the governing body and approve significant decisions of the governing body.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 11b: Form 990 Review Process
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The Organization's Treasurer works with the Organization's outside CPA firm on the preparation of the return. The return is then reviewed by the Treasurer and Audit Committee Chair prior to filing.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 12c: Explanation of Monitoring and Enforcement of Conflicts
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Each voting member of OMWB must disclose to the board via a conflict of interest questionnaire if she or any member of her immediate family or any organization with which she is affiliated, transacts or might transact business with OMWB, as defined in the conflict of interest policy. The member with any such relationship cannot vote on matters pertaining to or resulting in any benefit to that person or business. The Executive Committee/OMWB will review disclosures and decide if any conflict is pertinent to a vote by the membership and instruct the member not to vote on that matter. Such action will be reported in the minutes as stated in the policy.
